{"title_page": "Rock Is Dead Tour", "text_new": "{{Infobox concert tour\n| concert_tour_name     = Rock is Dead\n| image                 = omegasinginscomawhite.jpg\n| artist                = [[Marilyn Manson (band)|Marilyn Manson]]\n| album                 = ''[[Mechanical Animals]]''\n| start_date            = March 21, 1999\n| end_date              = August 8, 1999\n| number_of_shows       = 46 (planned)<br>43 (completed)\n| last_tour             = [[Beautiful Monsters Tour|Beautiful Monsters]]<br>(1999)\n| this_tour             = '''Rock Is Dead'''<br>(1999)\n| next_tour             = [[Guns, God and Government Tour|Guns, God and Government]]<br>(2000\u20132001)\n}}\n'''Rock Is Dead''' was a worldwide arena tour by American [[rock music|rock band]] [[Marilyn Manson (band)|Marilyn Manson]] in 1999. It was the second tour launched in support of their third full-length studio LP, ''[[Mechanical Animals]]'', which was released on September 15, 1998.\n\nThe tour was a [[rebranding]] of the [[Marilyn Manson (band)|Marilyn Manson]] and [[Hole (band)|Hole]] co-headlined [[Beautiful Monsters tour]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1430073/courtney-love-considers-manson-morissette-tours-hole-gets-six-cma-nods.jhtml |title=Courtney Love Considers Manson, Morissette Tours As Hole Gets Six CMA Nods |work=[[MTV News|MTV]] |publisher=[[Viacom Media Networks]] |date=1998-12-02 |accessdate=2011-03-07 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180907010325/http://www.mtv.com/news/1430073/courtney-love-considers-manson-morissette-tours-as-hole-gets-six-cma-nods/ |archivedate=2018-09-07 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1430066/marilyn-manson-hole-announce-two-months-worth-dates.jhtml |title=Marilyn Manson, Hole Announce Two Months Worth Of Dates |work=MTV |publisher=Viacom Media Networks |date=1999-01-27 |accessdate=2011-03-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1430061/manson-hole-get-tour-on-road.jhtml |title=Manson, Hole Get Tour On The Road |work=MTV |publisher=Viacom Media Networks |date=1999-03-02 |accessdate=2011-03-07}}</ref> While it was initially successful, Beautiful Monsters was marked by numerous and well-publicized fracases between the frontperson of each band on and off-stage.<ref name=\"MTV Courtney Talks About Tour\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1430069/courtney-talks-about-holemanson-tour.jhtml |title=Courtney Talks About Hole/Manson Tour |work=MTV |publisher=Viacom Media Networks |date=1999-01-07 |accessdate=2011-03-07}}</ref> The discord caused a fallout between the two groups which resulted in Hole's departure from the playbill.<ref name=\"MTV Hole Walks Out\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1430056/hole-walks-out-on-tour-manson-injury-postpones-several-dates.jhtml |title=Hole Walks Out On Tour, Manson Injury Postpones Several Dates |work=MTV |publisher=Viacom Media Networks |date=1999-03-15 |accessdate=2011-03-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1430058/hole-marilyn-manson-avoid-nostalgia-tour-rolls-into-seattle.jhtml |title=Hole, Marilyn Manson Avoid Nostalgia As Tour Rolls Into Seattle |work=MTV |publisher=Viacom Media Networks |date=1999-03-05 |accessdate=2011-03-07}}</ref> Marilyn Manson decided to continue the tour and gave the opening act, [[Monster Magnet]], equal billing as co-headliner for Rock is Dead.<ref name=\"notpersonal\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1430055/marilyn-manson-holes-departure-from-tour-not-personal-thing.jhtml |title=Marilyn Manson Says Hole's Departure From Tour \"Not A Personal Thing\" |work=MTV |publisher=Viacom Media Networks |date=1999-03-15 |accessdate=2011-03-07}}</ref>\n\nMarilyn Manson released two recordings that documented portions of the tour: a live video album titled ''[[God Is in the T.V.]]'' and a [[live album]] titled ''[[The Last Tour on Earth]]''.\n\n==Background and development==\n{{Further information|Beautiful Monsters Tour}}\n{{Quote box\n |quote = We're history after this. You'll get to see the crack of someone's ass (a reference to Manson's habit of dropping his pants onstage). It will be fun.|source =&mdash;Courtney Love, announcing their withdrawal from the Beautiful Monsters Tour.<ref name=\"thegirlgod\">{{cite journal |last1=Moran |first1=Caitlin |date=1999-09-01 |title=The Girl Who Wanted To Be God |journal=[[Select (magazine)|Select]] |publisher=[[Ascential|Ascential plc]] |volume= |issue= |pages=92 |doi= |url= |accessdate=}}</ref>\n|salign=center \n|width=27% \n|align=right \n|style=padding:8px;}} \nAfter a series of public spats between the extremely outspoken lead vocalists of [[Hole (band)|Hole]] and Marilyn Manson during their joint Beautiful Monsters Tour, Hole vocalist [[Courtney Love]] officially announced their withdrawal on March 14, 1999 as they took the stage at [[The Forum (Inglewood, California)|The Forum]] arena. They went on to do a series of shows in North America before leaving for the [[United Kingdom]] to join the [[Glastonbury Festival]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nme.com/news/hole/1361 |title=All's Fair in Love |work=[[NME]] |publisher=[[Time Inc. UK]] |date=1999-04-18 |accessdate=2015-07-15 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150715032258/http://www.nme.com/news/hole/1361 |archivedate=2015-07-15 }}</ref>\n\nDuring Marilyn Manson's performance on the night of Hole's departure, Manson suffered a hairline fracture on one of his ankles while jumping between on-stage platforms. His injury caused the tour to be temporarily suspended while he recuperated.<ref name=\"MTV Hole Walks Out\"/> The March 16, 1999 [[San Diego]], [[California]] concert was cancelled while the March 17, 1999 [[Las Vegas]], [[Nevada]] and March 18, 1999 [[Phoenix, Arizona|Phoenix]], [[Arizona]] engagements were postponed to a later date.<ref>{{cite magazine |first=Brannigan |last=Paul |date=October 2003 |title=All-American Reject |work=[[Kerrang!]] |issue=977 |pages=24\u201327 |publisher=[[Bauer Media Group]] |issn=0262-6624}}</ref> In spite of the highly-publicized animosity, Manson insisted Hole's departure was \"not a personal thing.\"<ref name=\"notpersonal\"/>\n\nThe tour resumed on March 21, 1999, rebranded as the Rock Is Dead Tour after the Marilyn Manson single \"[[Rock Is Dead (Marilyn Manson song)|Rock Is Dead]]\", despite the fact that the name was already being used by American rock bands [[Korn]] and [[Rob Zombie]] for their own concurrent joint US tour, the Rock is Dead! Tour.<ref>{{cite web |author=MTV News Staff |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1428836/jonathan-speaks-as-korn-rob-zombie-kick-off-rock-is-dead-tour/ |title=Jonathan Speaks as Korn, Rob Zombie Kick Off \"Rock Is Dead\" Tour |work=MTV |publisher=Viacom Media Networks |date=1999-03-01 |accessdate=2019-01-04 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190104092603/http://www.mtv.com/news/1428836/jonathan-speaks-as-korn-rob-zombie-kick-off-rock-is-dead-tour/ |archivedate=2019-01-04 }}</ref> This led to a minor dispute that was quickly resolved by both parties.<ref name=\"rocksurvival\">{{cite web |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1430057/marilyn-manson-talks-rock-survival-as-tour-with-hole-marches-on/ |title=Marilyn Manson Talks Rock Survival As Tour With Hole Marches On |work=MTV |publisher=Viacom Media Networks |date=1999-03-10 |accessdate=2015-07-14 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150726212136/http://www.mtv.com/news/1430057/marilyn-manson-talks-rock-survival-as-tour-with-hole-marches-on/ |archivedate=2015-07-26 }}</ref> Manson kept all of the remaining scheduled engagements intact.<ref name=\"Manson Taps Pussy\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1430051/manson-resumes-tour-without-hole-taps-nashville-pussy-jack-off-jill-upcoming-dates.jhtml |title=Manson Resumes Tour Without Hole, Taps Nashville Pussy And Jack Off Jill For Upcoming Dates |work=MTV |publisher=Viacom Media Networks |date=1999-03-22 |accessdate=2011-03-07 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180907010123/http://www.mtv.com/news/1430051/manson-resumes-tour-without-hole-taps-nashville-pussy-and-jack-off-jill-for-upcoming-dates/ |archivedate=2018-09-07 }}</ref>\n\nNow exercising full control over the tour's itinerary, Manson immediately withdrew [[Imperial Teen|Imperial Teen's]] billing in favor of [[Grammy]]-nominated American [[psychobilly]] band [[Nashville Pussy]], who took over the opening act slot from Monster Magnet beginning from the April 2, 1999 concert at the Memorial Coliseum in [[Winston-Salem, North Carolina]] until the completion of all North American dates on the tour. Manson explained to MTV that the initial inclusion of Imperial Teen on the tour was \"by Courtney's request. I think we're probably better off, because that would've been an additional torment for our fans that they didn't need.\" He added that while he enjoyed their music on [[Compact disc|CD]], he felt there was too much difference in their musical and performance approach for their continued inclusion on the tour to work.<ref name=\"Manson Taps Pussy\"/>\n\nFellow Floridians and longtime friends of the band [[Jack Off Jill]] joined Manson's tour for four dates from March 25, 1999, at the Uno Arena in [[New Orleans]] until March 30, 1999, at the National Car Center Arena in their shared hometown of [[Fort Lauderdale, Florida]], for both groups' homecoming concert.<ref name=\"Manson Taps Pussy\"/>\n\n==Performance and show themes==\n\"Inauguration of the Mechanical Christ\" was created as an intro for Marilyn Manson, who would appear fixed to a crucifix made out of television sets as it rose from beneath the stage.\n\nMarilyn Manson would also pose as an officer during \"Irresponsible Hate Anthem\" and as a finale, Manson's backup singer would arrive as a second officer with a shotgun. The shotgun would fire into Manson's back, splattering blood unto the crowd. With Manson having been 'murdered', his body would be dragged from the stage.\n\nThe podium scene during Antichrist Superstar continued to appear for the track of the same name. This led to a slight controversy during what was to be the original final North American tour date. During the Cedar Rapids, Iowa, show, Marilyn Manson was surprised to find the Antichrist Superstar logo on his podium had been replaced with a smiley face, ultimately leading to Manson walking off the stage and not returning.\n\nSet props included a massive lit sign spelling D-R-U-G-S, as well as golden confetti fired often from cannons.\n\n==Incidents==\nFollowing the aftermath of the [[Columbine High School massacre]] in [[Littleton, Colorado]],<ref>{{cite web|last=D'Angelo |first=Joe |last2=Vineyard |first2=Jennifer |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1442018/20010322/marilyn_manson.jhtml |title=Marilyn Manson Bows Out Of Denver Ozzfest Date |work=MTV |publisher=Viacom Media Networks |date=2001-05-22 |accessdate=2010-11-16}}</ref><ref name=\"Respers\"/> the band canceled the remaining dates of the tour out of respect for the victims, explaining, \"It's not a great atmosphere to be out playing rock 'n' roll shows, for us or the fans.\"<ref name=\"NYTimesStern\">{{cite news|last=Sterngold |first=James |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/04/29/us/terror-in-littleton-the-culture-rock-concerts-are-cancelled.html?ref=marilyn_manson |title=Terror in Littleton: The Culture; Rock Concerts Are Cancelled |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |publisher=[[A.G. Sulzberger]] |date=1999-04-29 |accessdate=2010-11-22}}</ref><ref name=\"BBC Manson cancels rest of US tour\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/331363.stm |title=Manson cancels rest of US tour |work=[[BBC News]] |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=1999-04-29 |accessdate=2010-11-18}}</ref><ref name=\"MTV Marilyn Manson cancelled\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1427257/19990422/story.jhtml |title=Marilyn Manson Concert, Other Denver Events Cancelled In Wake Of High School Shooting |work=MTV |publisher=Viacom Media Networks |date=1999-04-22 |accessdate=2010-11-16}}</ref> However, Manson steadfastly maintained that music, movies, books or video games are not to blame, stating,<ref name=\"NYTimesStern\"/><ref name=\"BBC Manson cancels rest of US tour\"/><ref name=\"MTV Marilyn Manson cancelled\"/>\n\n{{cquote|The [news] media has unfairly scapegoated the music industry and so-called Goth kids and has speculated, with no basis in truth, that artists like myself are in some way to blame. This tragedy was a product of ignorance, hatred and an access to guns. I hope the [news] media's irresponsible finger-pointing doesn't create more discrimination against kids who look different.<ref name=\"NYTimesStern\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1431704/marilyn-manson-postpones-us-tour-dates.jhtml |title=Marilyn Manson Postpones U.S. Tour Dates |work=MTV |publisher=Viacom Media Networks |date=1999-04-28 |accessdate=2011-03-21}}</ref>}}\n\n===Columbine High School massacre and its immediate aftermath===\n{{Further|Columbine High School massacre|Marilyn Manson\u2013Columbine High School massacre controversy}}\n{{Quote box |quote =I think there's something going on that you can't see from the outside ...&nbsp;his whole thing is part of a drug-cultural type of thing, with a subculture of violence and killing and hatred, and anti-family values, anti-traditional values, anti-authority&nbsp;... We're having an alarming rate of killings in schools, and youth violence and an increase in drugs. I would say that though they're not all to be blamed on a shock entertainer like Marilyn Manson, I think he promotes it and can be part of the blame. |source =&mdash;Michigan State Senator Dale Shugars' concerns on the influence of Marilyn Manson on concert-goers.<ref name=\"Manson Puts Fans Under Spell\">{{cite web |last=Nelson |first=Chris |url=http://www.vh1.com/news/articles/513702/19990422/index.jhtml |title=Best Of '99: Lawmaker Says Marilyn Manson Puts Fans Under Spell |work=[[VH1]] |publisher=Viacom Media Networks |date=1999-04-22 |accessdate=2011-05-03}}</ref> \n|salign=center \n|width=25% \n|align=right \n|style=padding:8px;}} \nOn April 20, 1999, [[Columbine High School]] students [[Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold]] shot dead 12 students and a teacher and wounded 21 others, before committing suicide.<ref name=\"Respers\">{{cite news |last=France |first=Lisa Respers |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2009/SHOWBIZ/04/20/columbine.pop.culture/index.html |title=Columbine left its indelible mark on pop culture |work=[[CNN]] |publisher=[[Turner Broadcasting System]], (Time Warner) |date=2009-04-20 |accessdate=2010-11-17 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160514002848/http://edition.cnn.com/2009/SHOWBIZ/04/20/columbine.pop.culture/index.html |archivedate=2016-05-14 |url-status=live }}</ref> In the aftermath of the [[school shooting]], the band were [[Marilyn Manson\u2013Columbine High School massacre controversy|widely reported to have influenced the killings]];<ref name=\"Screaming\">{{cite magazine |first=Tom|last=Bryant |date=2010-11-10 |title=Screaming For Vengeance |work=[[Kerrang!]] |issue=1338 |pages=40\u201342 |publisher=[[Bauer Media Group]] |issn=0262-6624}}</ref><ref name=\"Respers\"/> early media reports alleged that the shooters were fans, and were wearing the group's T-shirts during the massacre.<ref name=\"Cullen\">{{cite web|last=Cullen |first=Dave |url=http://www.salon.com/1999/09/23/columbine_4/ |title=Inside the Columbine High investigation |work=[[Salon (website)|Salon]] |publisher=Salon Media Group Inc. |date=1999-09-23 |accessdate=2012-05-15 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170517044320/http://www.salon.com/1999/09/23/columbine_4/ |archivedate=2017-05-17 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Manson bashing\">{{cite web|last=O'Connor |first=Christopher |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/513754/colorado-tragedy-continues-to-spark-manson-bashing/ |title=Colorado Tragedy Continues To Spark Manson Bashing |work=MTV |publisher=Viacom Media Networks |date=1999-04-27 |accessdate=2011-05-03 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161008181330/http://www.mtv.com/news/513754/colorado-tragedy-continues-to-spark-manson-bashing/ |archivedate=2016-10-08 |url-status=live}}</ref> Although these claims were later proven to be false,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/marilyn-manson-media-storm-after-columbine-really-shut-down-my-career-entirely/ |title=Marilyn Manson: Media Storm After Columbine 'Really Shut Down My Career Entirely' |work=[[Blabbermouth.net]] |publisher=Borivoj Krgin|date=2015-06-24 |accessdate=2017-06-04 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150627061551/http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/marilyn-manson-media-storm-after-columbine-really-shut-down-my-career-entirely/ |archivedate=2015-06-27 |url-status=live}}</ref> speculation in national media and among the public continued to blame Manson's music and imagery for inciting Harris and Klebold.<ref name=\"Screaming\"/> Later reports revealed that the two were not fans\u2014and, on the contrary, had disliked the band's music.<ref name=\"Columbinefault\">{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/culture/news/columbine-whose-fault-is-it-19990624 |title=Columbine: Whose Fault Is It? |author=Marilyn Manson |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |publisher=[[Wenner Media]] |date=1999-04-24 |accessdate=2017-06-20 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120721192522/http://www.rollingstone.com/culture/news/columbine-whose-fault-is-it-19990624 |archivedate=2012-07-21 |url-status=live}}</ref> Despite this, Marilyn Manson (as well as other bands and forms of entertainment, such as movies and video games) were widely criticized by religious,<ref name=\"Ape\">{{cite magazine|last1=Kessler |first1=Ted |date=2000-09-09 |title=Marilyn Manson Goes Ape |work=NME |volume= |issue= |pages=28\u201331 |publisher=Time Inc. UK |doi= |issn=0028-6362 |url= |accessdate=}}</ref> political,<ref name=\"Reexamination\">{{cite news|last=Burk |first=Greg |url=http://www.laweekly.com/news/marilyn-a-re-examination-2132874 |title=Marilyn: A Re-Examination |newspaper=[[LA Weekly]] |publisher=[[Village Voice Media]] |date=2001-01-18 |accessdate=2017-05-10 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160529211151/http://www.laweekly.com/news/marilyn-a-re-examination-2132874 |archivedate=2016-05-29 |url-status=live}}</ref> and entertainment-industry figures.<ref>{{cite web|last=Uhelszki |first=Jaan |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/lynyrd-skynyrd-threaten-marilyn-manson-with-a-can-of-whoop-ass-19990813 |title=Lynyrd Skynyrd Threaten Marilyn Manson With a Can of Whoop Ass |work=Rolling Stone |publisher=Wenner Media |date=1999-08-13 |accessdate=2011-06-09 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170519133714/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/lynyrd-skynyrd-threaten-marilyn-manson-with-a-can-of-whoop-ass-19990813 |archivedate=2017-05-19 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nA day after the shooting, [[Michigan Senate|Michigan State Senator]] Dale Shugars attended the band's concert, along with policy advisers, a local police officer and the state senate's sergeant-at-arms, at the [[Van Andel Arena]] in [[Grand Rapids, Michigan]] to conduct research for a proposed [[Bill (proposed law)|bill]] requiring parental warnings on concert tickets and promotional material for any performer that had released a record bearing the [[Parental Advisory|Parental Advisory sticker]] in the last five years.<ref name=\"Manson Puts Fans Under Spell\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/926161.stm |title=Directors call for tougher ratings |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=2000-09-15 |accessdate=2011-05-04}}</ref> According to Shugars, the show began with the singer wearing \"satanic wings\" as he leapt from a cross that was eventually set on fire.<ref name=\"Manson Puts Fans Under Spell\"/> He then described seeing fans, whom he described as normal kids, \"under [Manson's] control\" as he performed a sequence that \"glorified the killing of a police officer.\"<ref name=\"Manson Puts Fans Under Spell\"/> Finally, he reported the singer recounting a dream sequence in which cops perform sex acts on him before Jesus Christ descended out of a sky made of [[LSD]] and told him the real name of God is \"Drugs.\"<ref name=\"Manson Puts Fans Under Spell\"/> After which, the band launched into \"[[I Don't Like the Drugs (But the Drugs Like Me)]]\".<ref name=\"Manson Puts Fans Under Spell\"/> Shugars expressed concern that these shows had adverse effects on concert-goers.<ref name=\"Manson Puts Fans Under Spell\"/>\n\nOn April 25, 1999, longtime [[music industry]] critics, [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] former [[United States Secretary of Education|Secretary of Education]] [[William Bennett]] and [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] [[United States Senate|US Senator]] [[Joseph Lieberman]] called the group a contributing factor to the massacre during their appearance on ''[[Meet the Press]]''.<ref name=\"Manson bashing\"/><ref name=\"Manson bogey\">{{cite news|last=Strauss |first=Neil |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/05/17/arts/a-bogey-band-to-scare-parents-with.html |title=A Bogey Band to Scare Parents With |work=The New York Times |publisher=A.G. Sulzberger |date=1997-05-17 |accessdate=2011-05-03}}</ref> Three days later, the city of [[Fresno, California]] passed a unanimous resolution condemning \"Marilyn Manson or any other negative entertainer who encourages anger and hate upon the community as an offensive threat to the children of this community.\"<ref name=\"Fresno stay away\">{{cite web |url=http://www.vh1.com/news/articles/513786/19990428/index.jhtml |title=California City Asks Marilyn Manson To Stay Away |work=VH1 |publisher=Viacom Media Networks |date=1999-04-28 |accessdate=2011-05-03}}</ref> Its author, Councilman [[Henry Perea]], justified the resolution pointing out that people would face arrest if they publicly \"engaged in some of the same behaviors that [Manson] demonstrates onstage\"<ref name=\"VH1 Politicians Go On Offensive\">{{cite web |last=O'Connor |first=Christopher |url=http://www.vh1.com/news/articles/513908/19990501/index.jhtml |title=Politicians Go On Offensive Against Marilyn Manson |work=VH1 |publisher=Viacom Media Networks |date=1999-05-01 |accessdate=2011-05-04}}</ref> In [[Portsmouth, New Hampshire]], students were barred from wearing Marilyn Manson T-shirts in school premises.<ref name=\"Fresno stay away\"/> \n\n{{Quote box |quote =He or she or whatever the case might be realizes that he can be tremendously booed and that his work is tremendously offensive. |source =&mdash;US Senator Orrin Hatch's conjecture on why the band decided to abandon the rest of their US tour.<ref name=\"VH1 Senators Criticize\"/>\n|salign=center \n|width=30% \n|align=left \n|style=padding:8px;}} \nOn April 29, ten US senators (led by [[Sam Brownback]] of Kansas) sent a letter to [[Edgar Bronfman Jr.]] \u2013 the president of [[Seagram]] (the owner of Interscope) \u2013 requesting a voluntary halt to his company's distribution to children of \"music that glorifies violence\". The letter named Marilyn Manson for producing songs which \"eerily reflect\" the actions of Harris and Klebold.<ref name=\"outraged assholes write letter\">{{cite web |url=http://www.vh1.com/news/articles/513848/19990429/index.jhtml |title=Outraged Senators Write To Manson's Label |work=VH1 |publisher=Viacom Media Networks |date=1999-04-29 |accessdate=2011-05-03}}</ref> The signatories included eight Republicans and two Democrats namely, US Senators [[Wayne Allard]], [[Ben Nighthorse Campbell]], [[Susan Collins]], [[Tim Hutchinson]], [[Rick Santorum]], [[Kent Conrad]], [[Byron Dorgan]], [[John Ashcroft]] and [[Jeff Sessions]].<ref name=\"VH1 Politicians Go On Offensive\"/> Later that day, the band cancelled their remaining North American shows.<ref name=\"NYTimesStern\"/> Two days later, Manson published his response to these accusations in an [[op-ed]] piece for ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', titled \"Columbine: Whose Fault Is It?\", where he castigated [[Gun culture in the United States|America's gun culture]], the political influence of the [[National Rifle Association]], and the media's irresponsible coverage, which he said facilitated the placing of blame on a [[scapegoat]], instead of debating more relevant societal issues.<ref name=\"Columbinefault\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/nme/1434 |title=Marilyn Manson: The Write To Be Wrong |work=NME |publisher=Time Inc. UK |date=1999-05-01 |accessdate=2011-03-31 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120119100905/http://www.nme.com/news/nme/1434 |archivedate=2012-01-19 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn May 4, a hearing on the marketing and distribution of violent content to minors by the television, music, film and video-game industries was held by the [[United States Senate Committee on Commerce, Science and Transportation]]. The committee heard testimony from former [[United States Secretary of Education|Secretary of Education]] and [[FreedomWorks|Empower America]] co-founder [[William Bennett]], the Archbishop of Denver [[Charles J. Chaput]], professors and mental-health professionals. Speakers criticized the band, its label-mate [[Nine Inch Nails]], and the 1999 film ''[[The Matrix]]'' for their alleged contribution to a cultural environment enabling violence such as the Columbine shootings.<ref name=\"VH1 Senators Criticize\">{{cite web |last=O'Connor |first=Christopher |url=http://www.vh1.com/news/articles/513971/19990504/index.jhtml |title=Senators Criticize Marilyn Manson, Nine Inch Nails at Hearing |work=[[VH1]] |publisher=Viacom Media Networks |date=1999-05-04 |accessdate=2011-05-03 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120411233607/http://www.vh1.com/news/articles/513971/19990504/index.jhtml |archivedate=2012-04-11 |url-status=dead}}</ref> The committee requested that the [[Federal Trade Commission]] and the [[United States Department of Justice]] investigate the entertainment industry's marketing practices to minors.<ref name=\"VH1 Senators Criticize\"/><ref name=\"Salon Hollywood on Trial-1\">{{cite web |last=Tapper |first=Jake |url=http://www.salon.com/2000/08/29/hollywood_2/ |title=Hollywood on trial |work=Salon |publisher=Salon Media Group Inc. |date=2000-08-29 |accessdate=2012-05-15}}</ref> The CEOs of four of the world's largest music distributors declined the invitation to attend.<ref name=\"VH1 Senators Criticize\"/> Bennett denounced their absence and said it amounted to a \"[p]ublic shaming. My hunch is they will continue to ignore you like they did today.\"<ref name=\"VH1 Senators Criticize\"/> Outside observers such as Nina Crowley, director of the anti-censorship organization Mass Mic, expressed chagrin regarding the hearings, commenting that it was \"a very stacked-looking thing.\"<ref name=\"VH1 Senators Criticize\"/> [[Hilary Rosen]], president and CEO of the RIAA, shared this opinion and thought \"it was staged as political theater [...] They just wanted to find a way to shame the industry, and I'm not ashamed.\"<ref name=\"VH1 Senators Criticize\"/> \n \nSenators Brownback, Hatch and Lieberman concluded the proceedings by requesting an investigation from the [[Federal Trade Commission]] and the [[United States Department of Justice]] on marketing practices of the entertainment industry to minors.<ref name=\"VH1 Senators Criticize\"/><ref name=\"Salon Hollywood on Trial\">{{cite web |last=Tapper |first=Jake |url=http://www.salon.com/news/politics/feature/2000/08/29/hollywood/index.html |title=Hollywood on trial |work=Salon |publisher=Salon Media Group Inc. |date=2000-08-29 |accessdate=2011-05-04}}</ref> The following month, President [[Bill Clinton]] granted that request lamenting that \"kids steeped in the culture of violence do become desensitized to it and more capable of committing it.\"<ref name=\"Salon Hollywood on Trial\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Sylvester |first=Sherri |url=http://edition.cnn.com/SHOWBIZ/Movies/9906/30/movie.violence/index.html?iref=allsearch |title=Hollywood, government face off over violence in media |work=CNN |publisher=Turner Broadcasting System, (Time Warner) |date=1999-06-30 |accessdate=2011-05-04}}</ref> The release of the FTC report on September 13, led Lieberman, by then the [[2000 Democratic National Convention|vice presidential candidate]] on the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic ticket]], and [[Hillary Clinton]] to introduce the Media Marketing Accountability Act of 2001 before the [[107th United States Congress]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Mancini |first=Al |url=http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/story?id=106111&page=1 |title=Commentary: Media Violence Report Is Flawed |work=[[ABC News]] |publisher=[[Disney\u2013ABC Television Group]] |date=2000-04-26 |accessdate=2011-05-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Lieberman |first= Joseph|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/107th-congress/senate-bill/792 |title=S.792 - Media Marketing Accountability Act of 2001 |work=[[107th United States Congress]] |publisher=[[Congress.gov]] |date=2001-04-26 |accessdate=2018-12-29 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/921219.stm |title=Hollywood denies 'selling violence' |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=2000-09-12 |accessdate=2011-05-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/1398348.stm |title=Lieberman steps up Hollywood attack |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=2001-07-06 |accessdate=2011-05-04}}</ref> This legislation proposed to ban the entertainment-industry from marketing suspected violent or explicit material to minors.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2000/SHOWBIZ/News/11/06/hollywood.politics/index.html?iref=allsearch |title=Entertainment industry an issue, asset for presidential campaign |work=CNN |publisher=Turner Broadcasting System, (Time Warner) |date=2000-11-06 |accessdate=2011-05-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Eszterhas |first=Joe |url=http://www.salon.com/news/politics/feature/2000/09/14/hollywood |title=They came, they caved |work=Salon |publisher=Salon Media Group Inc.|date=2000-09-14 |accessdate=2011-05-04}}</ref>\n\nAfter concluding the European and Japanese legs of their tour on August 8, the band withdrew from public view.<ref name=\"Screaming\"/> Manson entered into a three-month period of seclusion at his home in the [[Hollywood Hills]],<ref name=\"AP#148\">{{cite magazine |first=Tom|last=Lanham |date=November 2000 |title=Marilyn Manson: Absinthe Makes The Heart Grow Fonder |work=[[Alternative Press (music magazine)|Alternative Press]] |issue=148 |pages=76\u201386 |issn=1065-1667}}</ref> during which he considered how to respond to the Columbine controversy.<ref name=\"Screaming\"/> Manson said the maelstrom made him re-evaluate his career: \"There was a bit of trepidation, [in] deciding: 'Is it worth it? Are people understanding what I'm trying to say? Am I even gonna be allowed to say it?' Because I definitely had every single door shut in my face&nbsp;... there were not a lot of people who stood behind me.\"<ref name=\"LoudwireHA\">{{cite web |url=http://loudwire.com/manson-holy-wood-album-anniversary/ |title=16 Years Ago: Marilyn Manson Emerges From the Eye of the Storm With 'Holy Wood' Album |first=Chad |last=Childers |work=[[Loudwire]] |publisher=[[Townsquare Media]] |date=2016-11-14 |accessdate=2017-04-26 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170128045914/http://loudwire.com/manson-holy-wood-album-anniversary/ |archivedate=2017-01-28 |url-status=live}}</ref> He told ''[[Alternative Press (music magazine)|Alternative Press]]'' that he felt his safety was threatened to the point that he \"could be [[Death of John Lennon|shot Mark David Chapman-style]].\"<ref name=\"AP#148\"/> He nevertheless found solace in writing new music which resulted in the band's 2000 album ''[[Holy Wood (In the Shadow of the Valley of Death)]]''.<ref name=\"AP#148\"/><ref name=\"LoudwireHA\"/> The singer described this record as his \"counterattack.\"<ref name=\"LoudwireHA\"/>\n\n==Recordings==\nMarilyn Manson released a live video album on November 2, 1999 titled ''[[God Is in the T.V.]]'' that contained rare and unreleased footage including a behind-the-scenes backstage look at some of the experiences the band underwent during the Rock Is Dead Tour. He also released a [[live album]] on November 12, 1999 titled ''[[The Last Tour on Earth]]'' that documented curated performances by his band from various concerts during the tour.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nme.com/news/marilyn-manson/1885 |title=Manson: Love Hate Hate Love |work=NME |publisher=Time Inc. UK |date=1999-05-28 |accessdate=2015-07-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150715152143/http://www.nme.com/news/marilyn-manson/1885 |archive-date=2015-07-15 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Lineup==\n;Marilyn Manson\n*[[Marilyn Manson]]: Vocals\n*[[John 5 (guitarist)|John 5]]: Guitar\n*[[Twiggy Ramirez]]: Bass\n*[[Madonna Wayne Gacy]]: Keyboards\n*[[Ginger Fish]]: Drums\n\n==Set List==\n{{Col-begin}}\n{{Col-break}}\n\n===North America===\n\n# \"Inauguration of the Mechanical Christ\"\n# \"The Reflecting God\"\n# \"Great Big White World\"\n# \"[[Get Your Gunn]]\"\n# \"Mechanical Animals\"\n# \"[[Sweet Dreams (Are Made of This)#Marilyn Manson cover|Sweet Dreams (Are Made of This)]]\" / \"[[Long Hard Road Out of Hell]]\" (Outro)\n# \"The Speed of Pain\"\n# \"[[Rock Is Dead (Marilyn Manson song)|Rock is Dead]]\"\n# \"[[The Dope Show]]\"\n# \"[[Lunchbox (song)|Lunchbox]]\"\n# \"[[I Don't Like the Drugs (But the Drugs Like Me)]]\"\n# \"Irresponsible Hate Anthem\"\n# \"[[Antichrist Superstar (song)|Antichrist Superstar]]\"\n# \"[[The Beautiful People (Marilyn Manson song)|The Beautiful People]]\"\n{{Col-break}}\n\n===Europe/Asia===\n\n# \"Inauguration of the Mechanical Christ\"\n# \"The Reflecting God\"\n# \"Great Big White World\"\n# \"Cake and Sodomy\"\n# \"Sweet Dreams (Are Made of This)\" / \"Long Hard Road Out of Hell\" (Outro)\n# \"[[Astonishing Panorama of the Endtimes]]\"\n# \"Rock is Dead\"\n# \"The Dope Show\"\n# \"Lunchbox\"\n# \"I Don't Like the Drugs (But the Drugs Like Me)\"\n# \"[[Rock N Roll Nigger]]\"\n# \"The Beautiful People\"\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Tour dates==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+ List of concerts, showing date, city, country, venue and opening act\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:12em;\"| Date\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:10em;\"| City\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:10em;\"| Country\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:16em;\"| Venue\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:10em;\"| Opening Act(s)\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:10em;\"| Attendance\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:10em;\"| Revenue\n|- \n! colspan=\"7\"|Leg 1 \u2014 North America\n|-\n| 21 March 1999\n| rowspan=\"1\"|[[Houston]]\n| rowspan=\"28\"|United States\n| rowspan=\"1\"|[[Lakewood Church Central Campus|The Summit (aka Compaq Center)]]\n| rowspan=\"3\"|[[Monster Magnet]]\n| {{n/a}}\n| {{n/a}}\n|-\n| 22 March 1999\n| rowspan=\"1\"|[[San Antonio, Texas|San Antonio]]\n| rowspan=\"1\"|[[Alamodome]]\n| {{n/a}}\n| {{n/a}}\n|-\n| 23 March 1999\n| rowspan=\"1\"|[[Dallas, Texas|Dallas]]\n| rowspan=\"1\"|[[Reunion Arena]]\n| {{n/a}}\n| {{n/a}}\n|-\n| 25 March 1999\n| rowspan=\"1\"|[[New Orleans]]\n| rowspan=\"1\"|[[UNO Arena]]\n| rowspan=\"4\"|[[Jack Off Jill]]\n| {{n/a}}\n| {{n/a}}\n|-\n| 27 March 1999\n| rowspan=\"1\"|[[Tampa, Florida|Tampa]]\n| rowspan=\"1\"|[[Ice Palace (Tampa arena)|Ice Palace]]\n| {{n/a}}\n| {{n/a}}\n|-\n| 29 March 1999\n| rowspan=\"1\"|[[Orlando, Florida|Orlando]]\n| rowspan=\"1\"|[[Orlando Arena]]\n| {{n/a}}\n| {{n/a}}\n|-\n| 30 March 1999\n| rowspan=\"1\"|[[Fort Lauderdale, Florida|Fort Lauderdale]]\n| rowspan=\"1\"|[[National Car Rental Center Arena]]\n| {{n/a}}\n| {{n/a}}\n|-\n| 2 April 1999\n| rowspan=\"1\"|[[Winston-Salem, North Carolina|Winston-